ingredients of wrath and fury; and the words may be rendered here,
"which is mixed without mixture": and though it seems to carry in it a
contradiction, yet is true in different senses; it may be said to be
mixed as wine with various sorts, which is the stronger, and sooner
inebriates and intoxicates; or in allusion to the cup the Jews gave to
malefactors, to stupefy them, when going to execution, which had various
things put in it for that purpose; See Gill on [Mar
15:23](../../../bib/kjv/mar015.htm#023.md) and so designs the several
